Busybox vi doesn’t work very well with UTF-8.  This *improves* things
but doesn’t fix all the issues.

What this fixes:

* Moving the cursor in UTF-8 text now keeps the cursor in the right place.
* The cursor no longer jumps when adding UTF-8 text.
* Using “i” to insert text on a line with UTF-8 has the line look correct 
  as the text is being inserted (this is an ugly hack: We refresh the entire
  line every time we add a character to the line; the hack includes passing
  an integer to a function which is supposed to get a boolean).

What is still really buggy:

* To delete UTF-8 text, “x” needs to be pressed multiple times to delete
  the character.  
* It will break the terminal if we delete a UTF-8 char at
  the beginning of the file. Workaround: Insert an ASCII character at the 
  top before deleting Unicode.
* “r” will not correctly replace a UTF-8 codepoint, but only the first
  octet (byte) in the UTF-8 sequence.  Use “x” multiple times then “i” to
  replace a UTF-8 character.

--- editors/vi.c.orig	2026-05-03 22:33:28.550102700 -0600
+++ editors/vi.c	2026-05-04 01:34:23.760779200 -0600
